<$fill $name="body">

!! Module overview

diffsync has three JS modules and two views:

|!File |!Module type |!Role |
|`diff-hunks.js` |library |Diff computation, hunk grouping, text reconstruction, field comparison, config helper |
|`action-diffsync.js` |widget |`<$action-diffsync>` action widget -- orchestrates compare, apply, and clear operations |
|`auto-refresh.js` |startup (browser) |Wiki change listener -- re-compares when source or target tiddler changes |
|`panel.tid` |-- |Interactive UI: tiddler pickers, diff display, hunk toggles, apply buttons |
|`review.tid` |-- |Review mode: accept/skip per change with batch actions |

!! Diff pipeline

The diff pipeline in `diff-hunks.js` works in three stages:

!!! 1. Line-level diff

`lineDiff(sourceText, targetText)` uses `diff_linesToChars_` / `diff_main` / `diff_charsToLines_` from TW's bundled diff-match-patch library. This converts text to per-line tokens, diffs the tokens, then maps back to line strings. The result is an array of `[type, text]` tuples where type is `DIFF_DELETE` (-1), `DIFF_INSERT` (1), or `DIFF_EQUAL` (0).

!!! 2. Hunk computation

`computeHunks(sourceText, targetText, contextLines)` takes the line diff and:

# Splits each diff tuple into individual line objects `{type, text}`
# Finds contiguous change regions (runs of non-equal lines)
# Wraps each region with `contextLines` lines of equal text before and after
# Merges overlapping context regions into a single hunk
# Returns an array of `{id, lines}` hunks

!!! 3. Text reconstruction

`reconstructText(sourceText, targetText, hunks, selections)` rebuilds the final text based on per-hunk user selections:

# Re-runs `lineDiff` to get the full line sequence
# Maps each line to its containing hunk (if any) by walking both sequences in parallel
# Walks all lines: equal lines are always kept; for changed lines inside a hunk, if the hunk is selected as "source", keep delete lines (source text) and skip insert lines (target text); default is "use target" (keep inserts, skip deletes)

!! Field comparison model

`compareFields(wiki, sourceTitle, targetTitle, contextLines)` compares two tiddlers:

* Takes the union of all field names from both tiddlers
* Skips `title` (always differs)
* Stringifies values: `Date` via `$tw.utils.stringifyDate`, arrays via `$tw.utils.stringifyList`, everything else via `String()`
* Detects multiline fields (any value containing `\n`)
* For multiline fields, computes hunks; for single-line fields, stores source/target values directly
* Returns an array of diff entries with `field`, `sourceVal`, `targetVal`, `sourceOnly`, `targetOnly`, `isMultiline`, and optionally `hunks`

!! State management

All state is stored in wiki tiddlers:

|!Tiddler |!Purpose |
|`$:/temp/diffsync/result` |JSON array of field diff entries (type `application/json`); also stores `source` and `target` fields for reference |
|`$:/state/diffsync/source` |Currently selected source tiddler title |
|`$:/state/diffsync/target` |Currently selected target tiddler title |
|`$:/state/diffsync/field/<fieldName>` |Per-field selection: `"source"` or empty (= target) |
|`$:/state/diffsync/field/<fieldName>/hunk/<id>` |Per-hunk selection for multiline fields: `"source"` or empty |

On each new comparison, all `$:/state/diffsync/field/*` tiddlers are deleted. The clear operation also deletes the result tiddler.

!! Auto-refresh

`auto-refresh.js` is a browser-side startup module that registers a wiki change listener. When the source or target tiddler (as recorded in `$:/temp/diffsync/result`) is modified:

# Re-runs `compareFields` using `getContextLines` to read the current config
# Stores the updated result JSON in `$:/temp/diffsync/result`
# Cleans up stale selection state tiddlers for fields/hunks that no longer exist in the new diff

This keeps the diff view live -- edits to either tiddler are reflected immediately without manually re-clicking Compare.

!! Apply logic

The `<$action-diffsync>` widget supports four operations:

* ''compare'' -- runs `compareFields`, stores result, clears old selections
* ''apply'' -- applies selected changes to the target tiddler
* ''apply-to-source'' -- applies selected changes to the source tiddler (inverts the selection logic)
* ''clear'' -- deletes result and all selection state tiddlers

For the apply operations, multiline fields use `reconstructText` with the hunk selections gathered from state tiddlers. For apply-to-source, selections are inverted: unselected hunks become "source" (since source/target are swapped in the reconstruction call). Single-line fields use the direct source/target value based on the toggle state.

</$fill>
</$transclude>
